<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-06-04T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-06-04T23:00:00-05:00" n="764" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d764">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">693.003/578: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Tenney</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-06-05T12:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">June 5,
                                            1920—noon</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received June 5—9:37
                                    a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>127. The Chinese Government urges reply to its note of February 27th,
                                transmitted by Legation April 7th.<note n="84" xml:id="d764fn84">See
                                    footnote 83, <ref target="#pg_733">p. 733</ref>.</note> I
                                request authorization to reply in the sense of British
                                recommendation quoted in the Legation despatch number 3207 or if
                                Department prefers to assent to immediate 5 per cent revision and
                                increase with abolition of likin.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Tenney</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>